Welcome to the Nemoh wiki!

#### Nemoh User Manual

1. 1.Introduction

NEMOH is a hydrodynamic radiation/diffraction panel code which uses a Boundary Element Method (BEM) to compute the first order wave loads on offshore structures (added mass, radiation damping, and diffraction forces). NEMOH is typically used for estimating the dynamic response and hydrodynamic loading of floating structures such as ships and Wave Energy Converters. Unlike other hydrodynamic BEM software, NEMOH&#39;s approach decouples the resolution of the linear free surface Boundary Value Problem (BVP) and the definition of the boundary condition on the body (body condition). This feature makes it easy to deal with flexible structures, hydro-elasticity, generalised modes and unconventional degrees of freedom within the NEMOH framework.

NEMOH was initially developed at Ecole Centrale de Nantes and was released as the world&#39;s first open source BEM code in January 2014 when it was released under the terms of the Apache 2 licence. Terms of the license may be found at [CITATION The04 \l 2057]. The software is now developed by the Nemoh Developer Group where any and all interested partied are invited to contribute to the ongoing community development. Nemoh Version XXX was released on XXX and is the current stable release of the NEMOH Software.

1. 2.Getting Started

This section details the installation and basic running of the NEMOH software. As NEMOH does not have a Graphical User Interface (GUI) users must set up a viable run through the generation of input text files prior to implementation of the NEMOH software. Once a viable run is established, NEMOH can be executed either through the command line (or equivalent alternative) or through an externally scripted call (such as through the Matlab program).

1.
  1. 1.1Software Structure

The NEMOH software is primarily composed of three separate programs which should be executed sequentially to complete a single run. The three programs are entitled &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_, &#39;_solver&#39;_ and &#39;_postProcessor&#39;_. As the names suggest the intended running order is; (1) _preProcessor_, (2) _solver_ and (3) _postProcessor_. Figure 1 provides an outline of the main NEMOH software structure. Note that throughout this document, reference to &#39;NEMOH&#39; refers to the combination of the _preProcessor_, _solver_ and _postProcessor_ sub-programs.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 1: Primary NEMOH Software Structure

The following list details the outline operations of each component program of the NEMOH software:

- The aim of the &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_ program is to prepare the mesh and to generate the body conditions for each calculation case (radiation and diffraction). Calculation cases are defined in the input file &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;,_ which must be located in the &#39;_Working Folder_&#39;.

- The aim of the &#39;_solver&#39;_ program is to solve the linear Boundary Value Problem (BVP) for each problem defined in the file Normalvelocities.dat. The calculation depends on parameters which are read in the file &#39;_input.txt&#39;_, located in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_.

- The aim of the &#39;_postProcessor&#39;_ program is to post-process the results in order to provide the relevant quantities (added mass, radiation damping, excitation force) in the usual format. It also provides a framework to make various relevant calculations at the user&#39;s request.

- The NEMOH software also includes a fourth, optional program which may be used for easy generation of simple axisymmetric meshes. This fourth optional program is entitled &#39;_mesh_&#39;. Note that throughout this document, when NEMOH is referred to, the use of the sub-program &#39;_mesh&#39;_ is not intended as it is not assumed to form part of the core NEMOH software.

All NEMOH software component programs have been written in Fortran.

  1. 1.2Installation and Setup

At present there are a number of ways to install the NEMOH software as due to the open-source nature of the program, not only are the operational executables (compiled programs) provided, users can also download the source code and compile NEMOH themselves.

  1.

Executable versions of the NEMOH software are not provided for Linux platforms and so users must compile their own versions of the component programs. A &#39;_makefile&#39;_ is provided with the source code for compiling NEMOH in Linux environments. The Intel Fortran compiler &#39;_ifort_&#39; should be used for compiling the NEMOH software in Linux. Other compilers may compile with small adjustments to the libraries. Code dependencies are the same as for compiling in Win32 environments.

Executable versions of the NEMOH software are not provided for Mac OS X platforms and so users must compile their own versions of the component programs. A &#39;_makefile_&#39; is provided with the source code for compiling NEMOH in Mac OS X environments. The &#39;_gfortran_&#39; compiler should be used for compiling the NEMOH software in a Mac OS X environment. Other compilers may compile with small adjustments to the libraries. Code dependencies are the same as for compiling in Win32 environments.

1.
  1. 1.3Running NEMOH

The NEMOH software is composed of three main programs (preProcessor, solver and postProcessor) which should be executed sequentially in a particular location to complete a single NEMOH run. The location within which the software should be implemented is hereafter referred to as the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ (see Section 2.3.1Suggested File &amp; Folder Structure). The &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ simply refers to the highest level folder within which all necessary files for a single NEMOH run are stored. It is highly recommended that a separate &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ (along with an appropriate subfolder structure) is generated for each separate NEMOH run completed. The simplest way to ensure NEMOH program access to the appropriate directory is to copy the relevant executable files (usually preProcessor, solver and postProcessor) into a given &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_. The software can then be called within this directory with relative ease.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.3.1Suggested File &amp; Folder Structure

For the NEMOH software to operate correctly the individual programs must be executed in a directory containing the correct sub-folder structure. The required folder structure is outlined in Figure 2. Figure 2 also lists the essential input files required within each folder to ensure successful execution of the NEMOH software. Note that additional, optional input files may also be included as detailed in &#39;_Section_ _4.2__Optional NEMOH Input files_&#39;.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 2: Required NEMOH Run Folder Structure

The top level folder has been termed &#39;_Working Folder&#39;._ This simply refers to a directory within which all components for a single NEMOH run are contained. The name of the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ folder is not important and may be defined by the user for ease of reference. Within this document the term &#39;_Working Folder_&#39; is simply used to refer to the directory within the NEMOH software will be executed.

In order for NEMOH to run successfully the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ must contain 2 sub-folders named &#39;_mesh&#39;_ and &#39;_results&#39;_. Note that the names of these two sub-folders are important and case-sensitive.

In addition to the specific sub-folder structure a user must also generate a number of text-based input data files for the NEMOH software to use. These input text files will be used to detail the parameters of the hydrodynamic problems to be solved. There are 4 essential text files which must be generated in order to use the NEMOH software. These are; (1) the &#39;_ID.dat_&#39; file, (2) the &#39;_input.txt_&#39; file, (3) the &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;_ file and (4) the &#39;_Mesh.dat&#39;_ file. The name and case of the &#39;_ID.dat_&#39; file, the &#39;_input.txt_&#39; file and the &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;_ file must all be exact as shown above. These files detail the input hydrodynamic parameters of the simulation and must all be present in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;._ The name of the &#39;_Mesh.dat&#39;_ file is unimportant as the user will identify this file within the &#39;_Nemoh.cal_&#39; file however the file must maintain a &#39;_.dat&#39;_ extension. A copy of the &#39;_Mesh.dat_&#39; file must be present in both the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ and in the &#39;_mesh&#39;_ sub-folder. For more details on input files please see &#39;_Section_ _4__Input Files_&#39;.

It is advised that a copy of the primary NEMOH executables, &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_, &#39;_solver&#39;_ and &#39;_postProcessor&#39;_, are placed in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_. This will allow for ease of access at the point of execution. Any additional NEMOH component programs required (such as &#39;_mesh.exe&#39;_ should also be included in this location). The resulting folder and file structure should look similar to that shown in Figure 3 where the primary executable programs have been included in _italic__font_ for ease of inspection.

    1. 1.3.2Running NEMOH from the Command Line/Terminal

Running NEMOH from the command line is necessary to make use of the full capabilities of the code, such as generalized or additional modes. In order to execute NEMOH from the command line the user should utilize an appropriate program (such as the _Command Prompt_ in a Microsoft Windows environment or the _Terminal_ in a Linux environment) and direct the current path to that of the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_. Assuming a copy of the appropriate executables (&#39;_preProcessor&#39;_, &#39;_solver&#39;_ and &#39;_postProcessor&#39;_) exists in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ the user should be able to simply execute the codes in sequential order as required by their particular operating system.

Some users might find it beneficial to write a short script which will run all 3 programs in the correct sequence to minimize user interaction required (for example a Bash file for Linux or a Batch file for Windows). This file may then be located in the same &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ and implemented on its own to execute all 3 (or more) programs according to the user defined operations. 1.
  1. 1.4The NEMOH Coordinate System and Reference Frame

Naturally it is important that modelled bodies are orientated correctly within the fluid domain. The global coordinate system and frame of reference assumed by the NEMOH software follows the &#39;Right Hand Rule&#39; and is summarised in Figure 5.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 5: NEMOH Global Coordinate System

As shown in Figure 5, the origin (O) of the NEMOH coordinate system is set on the mean free water surface. The horizontal plane z = 0 defines the free surface at rest. The vertical z-axis is positive vertically upwards. Typically waves are modelled as propagating along the x-axis (in the positive direction) when orientated with a heading of 0 is requested. Increasing the wave heading direction will tend to shift the propagation direction in an anticlockwise fashion when looking down onto the free water surface, i.e. an applied wave heading direction of 90 will result in wave propagation along the y-axis (in the positive direction). The bed level is set according to the user specified water depth parameter, h.

Under typical conditions bodies will be placed within the model domain according to the coordinates used during mesh generation. If additional bodies are to be modelled then additional mesh files must be generated for each body and those same mesh files must be identified in the &#39;_Nemoh.cal_&#39; file as explained in &#39;_Section_ _7__Analysis of Multiple Bodies_&#39;.

  11. 1.16Kochin Functions

Nemoh includes the capability of generating values for the Kochin Functions. Kochin Functions define the far-field velocity potential due to diffraction and radiation of a body. Because the Kochin Functions define the far-field velocity potential they do not include the potential due to evanescent waves, but only propagating waves. Kochin Functions, also called far-field potential functions, are defined by the equation

~k(r,,)=Aei(kr+B)krH(,)

Where ~k is the far-field diffraction or radiation velocity potential, H(,) is the complex Kochin Function in the direction  for a wave incident at the angle . Then, kr is the non-dimensional distance from the body and _A, B_ are constants dependent on the definition of the Kochin Function. Unfortunately there is no universally agreed definition for the Kochin function and the values of the constants _A_ and_B_ vary with the definition.

In Nemoh the Kochin function is defined as (see Delhommeau [1987] Eq 2.88 on page 80)

~k(r,,,z)=8k(Kh)2kh((kh)2(Kh)2+Kh)coshk(z+h)sinhkh1rei(kr+4)H(,)

1. 4.Input Files

The NEMOH software package does not include a Graphical User Interface (GUI). Users interact with the software by generating a number of text-based input files which the software will read from upon execution. It is therefore vitally important that the format and location of these files is precise to ensure NEMOH correctly interprets the user&#39;s intended simulation parameters. Text-based input files may be generated using any text editor however it is worth noting that certain text editors may display formatted files slightly differently, particularly when switching between multiple operating systems.

In order to successfully execute NEMOH the user must generate the four essential text-based input files. In addition, NEMOH allows for additional functionality to be implemented using additional, optional text-based input files. Note that NEMOH also requires particular placement of the various input files within the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ and its various sub-folders. For more detail on file placement see &#39;_Section_ _2.3.1 __Suggested File &amp; Folder Structure__&#39;_ and the entries for each specific input file containing within this section. The following sub-sections detail the format and functionality of the various essential and optional input files.

1.
  1. 1.17Essential NEMOH Input Files

This sub-section details each of the four essential text-based input files required by NEMOH to perform a successful run at the point of execution.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.17.1The &#39;_ID.dat_&#39; File

The &#39;_ID.dat&#39;_ file is used to generate an identification tag for the calculation. It must be located in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ where the NEMOH program is executed. The second line of the file should be a string of characters. This string should be the name of the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_. The first line should be the length of the string. Here is an example of the format of a suitable &#39;_ID.dat&#39;_ file:

| 7. | _This is the number of characters in the Working Folder name (row 2)_ |
| --- | --- |
| example | _This is the Working Folder name_ |

To be expanded

An example &#39;_ID.dat&#39;_ file is included in Appendix XXX. The &#39;_ID.dat&#39;_ file should be placed in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ prior to execution of the NEMOH software.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.17.2The &#39;_input.txt_&#39; File

The &#39;_input.txt_&#39; file allows the user to select the solver to be used for the simulation. Options include:

- 0         Solver
- 1        Direct Gauss
- 2        GMRES with FMM acceleration (not yet implemented)

The first line of the &#39;_input.txt&#39;_ file is unused and is generally set to &#39;_--- Calculation parameters ---&#39;._ The second line of the &#39;_input.txt&#39;_ file is used by the user to select the solver as indicated above. The format should be a single numeric digit selected from the list above. Often a comment will follow (denoted by the prefix of an exclamation mark &#39;_!_&#39;).

To be expanded

Here is an example of the format of a suitable &#39;_input.txt&#39;_ file:

| Calculation parameters |   |
| --- | --- |
| 0 | _Solver Selection_ |

1.
  1.
    1. 1.17.4The &#39;_Mesh.dat_&#39; File

The &#39;_Mesh.dat_&#39; file us used to specify the body mesh which will be simulated in NEMOH. NEMOH meshes must be composed of flat quadrangular panels and only the submerged part of the body at the equilibrium position should be described. In order for the mesh to be correctly implemented, the input data must be in the correct format as required by the program. Triangular panels may be used however one node should be duplicated.

The required format of a mesh file is as follows:

| **2** | **1** |   |   | _First number must be 2. Second number is 1 if symmetry about the (xOz) plane is used. 0 for no symmetry._ |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **1** | **2.** | **0.** | **-10.** | _Table of nodes. First number is the node ID. Subsequent numbers are x y and z coordinates respectively_ |
| **.** | **.** | **.** | **.** | _ List of nodes._ |
| **0** | **0.** | **0.** | **0.** | _Last line of the table of nodes  should be four zeros with decimal points_ |
| **1** | **2** | **3** | **4** | _Table of connectivities. This line details the numbers of node IDs use to form each panel. This example connects nodes 1, 2, 3 and 4._ |
| **.** | **.** | **.** | **.** | _ List of node connectivities._ |
| **0** | **0** | **0** | **0** | _Last line of table of connectivities  should be four zeros_ |

The sketch below shows the orientation convention used to describe the panel as seen looking from the fluid domain into the body.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

It is extremely important that this convention is adhered to and implemented correctly as NEMOH will use this approach to determine which side of a panel represents the wetted surface of a body. If this convention is not correctly adopted, results will still be produced however they will not be correct.

Within the framework of the NEMOH software it is possible to consider several bodies acting independently and to assess the hydrodynamic interactions. This is achieved by meshing each body separately and including detailing for each in the &#39;_Nemoh.cal_&#39; file. The final mesh will be assembled and built appropriately by the &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_.

Note that &#39;_Mesh.dat&#39;_ files may be given any name desired by the user. That same name should be specified in the appropriate location in the &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;_ file however to ensure the correct body is modelled. Note also that meshes may be generated in any number of manners, including through the use of meshing CAD packages such as Salome. It is worth noting however that not all &#39;_.dat_&#39; files will have a similar format and so manipulation of &#39;_.dat_&#39; files generated elsewhere may be required prior to execution of the NEMOH software. For more on methods of generating meshes readers are directed to Appendix XXX. Readers are also advised of mesh checking companion programs which can be used to assess the correctness of a &#39;_Mesh.dat_&#39; file to be used with NEMOH. For more on companion programs readers are directed to Appendix XXX.

An example &#39;_Mesh.dat&#39;_ file is included in Appendix XXX. Two copies of the &#39;_Mesh.dat_&#39; file are required for NEMOH to run. The &#39;_Mesh.dat&#39;_ file should be placed both in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ and the &#39;_mesh_&#39; sub-folder prior to execution of the NEMOH software.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.18.2Modelling of Kochin Functions

To output the Kochin function the Nemoh.calfile needs to be modified to define the number of angles and the angular resolution at which the Kochin Functions should be calculated. The line has the format

[_NumberAngles_]        [_MinimumAngle_]        [_MaximumAngle_]

The  _MinimumAngle_ and _MaximumAngle_ are defined in degrees relative to the _x_-axisi.

If the _NumberAngles_ is equal to 0 then the Kochin Functions are not calculated. If the _NumberAngles_ is equal to 1 then the _MinimumAngle_ is used to calculate the Kochin Functions. If the _NumberAngles_ is greater than 1 then the Kochin Function is calculated at evenly spaced intervals between the _MinimumAngle_ and _MaximumAngle_ inclusive.

1. 5.Output Files

Upon execution of the various component programs the NEMOH software generates various output files for user inspection and use. This section details the output files generated by each component program.

1.
  1. 1.19NEMOH preProcessor Output Files

This section details the files created by the NEMOH &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_. During this process files are created in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ as well as in both the &#39;_mesh&#39;_ and &#39;_results&#39;_ sub-folders which must already be present in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_ prior to execution of the NEMOH software.

Once the &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_ has been run successfully, the following files are created in the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_:

-
  - Normalvelocities.dat
  - Integration.dat

The following files are created in the &#39;_mesh_&#39; sub-folder:

-
  - L12.dat
  - L10.dat
  - Mesh.tec

The following files are created in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder:

-
  - FKForce.dat
  - FKForce.tec
  - FreeSurface.dat
  - Kochin.dat
  - index.dat

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.1The &#39;_Normalvelocities.dat_&#39; File

This file contains the body conditions for each radiation and diffraction problem defined in the Nemoh.cal file.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.2The &#39;_Integration.dat_&#39; File

This file contains the information about how the pressure has to be integrated over the body surfaces to obtain the requested forces (as defined in the Nemoh.cal file).

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.3The &#39;_L12.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_mesh_&#39; sub-folder. It contains the table of nodes and connectivities.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.4The &#39;_L10.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_mesh_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains mesh-based geometrical information such as use of symmetry about the (xOz) plane, number of nodes, number of panels, number of bodies, panel to body belonging matrix, panel centres, panel normal vectors and panel areas.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.5The &#39;_Mesh.tec_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_mesh_&#39; sub-folder. This file is saved in a Tecplot compatible format for visualisation purpose of the resultant mesh used at runtime of the NEMOH software.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.6The &#39;_FKForce.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. Froude Krylov forces for each of the diffraction problem.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.7The &#39;_FKForce.tec_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. As with the &#39;_FKForce.dat&#39;_ file this file contains Froude Krylov forces for each of the diffraction problem. The format of this second file is compatible with Tecplot. It may be used for vizualisation of Froude Krylov forces.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.8The &#39;_FreeSurface.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains the coordinates of the free surface where to calculate the wave elevation.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.9The &#39;_Kochin.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains the angle for which the Kochin function will be calculated.

This file can be found in the Mesh folder and contains the angles at which the Kochin function is calculated. It has the format

[_NumberAngles_]
[_AngleD1_]
[_AngleD2_]

[_AngleDN_]

The angles (_AngleD1_, _AngleD2_, , _AngleDN_) are defined in radians from the _x_-axisii

1.
  1.
    1. 1.19.10The &#39;_index.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This table gives correlation between force ID number, body ID number on which it applies and number if the Nemoh.cal file. It also contains the correlation between ID number of radiation problem, ID of body which is actually moving and the number of degree of freedom.

  1. 1.20NEMOH solver Output Files

This section details the files created by the NEMOH &#39;_solver&#39;_. During this process files are created in the &#39;_results&#39;_ sub-folder of the &#39;_Working Folder&#39;_. Note the &#39;_results&#39;_ sub-folder must have been created prior to execution of the NEMOH software.

Once the &#39;_solver&#39;_ has been run successfully, the following files are created in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder:

-
  - Forces.dat
  - freesurface.XX.dat
  - Kochin.XX.dat
  - Pressure.XX.dat

1.
  1.
    1. 1.20.1The &#39;_Forces.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains the forces resulting from each problem.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.20.2The &#39;_freesurface.XX.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains the free surface elevation for problem number XX.

1.
  1.
    1. 1.20.3The &#39;_Kochin.XX.dat_&#39; File

These files can be found in the Results folder and contains the values of the Kochin function at all the defined angles for the associated Problem. Note that the filenames contain spaces so that the total of the spaces plus digits is equal to six. The contents of each file has the format

[_AngleR1_][_MagnitudeKochinFunction@AngleR1_][_PhaseKochinFunction@AngleR1_]
[_AngleR2_] [_MagnitudeKochinFunction@AngleR2_][_PhaseKochinFunction@AngleR2_]

[_AngleRN_] [_MagnitudeKochinFunction@AngleRN_][_PhaseKochinFunction@AngleRN_]

The angles (_AngleR1_, _AngleR2_, , _AngleRN_) are defined in radians from the _x_-axisiii. The magnitude of the diffraction Kochin Function is per unit wave amplitude, the magnitude of the radiation Kochin Function is per unit modal velocity. The phase for both the diffraction and radiation Kochin Functions is in radians.

The files are numbered based on the associated Problem. The ordering of the files is given byiv

- [Loop over the number of wave frequencies]
  - [Loop over the number of wave directions]
    - Increment file number
    - File containing diffraction Kochin Function values
  - [End loop over wave directions]
- [End loop over wave frequencies]
- [Loop over the number of body modes]
  - [Loop over the number of wave frequencies]
    - Increment file number
    - File containing radiation Kochin Function values
  - [End loop over wave frequencies]
- [End loop over body modes]

1.
  1.
    1. 1.20.4The &#39;_Pressure.XX.dat_&#39; File

This file is saved in the &#39;_results_&#39; sub-folder. This file contains the pressure field on body surfaces for problem XX.

1. 6.Using Additional/Generalised Modes

Within the framework of the NEMOH software it is possible to model systems which have non-conventional degrees of freedom. For example it is possible to model bodies with &#39;additional modes&#39; beyond the standard 6 degrees of freedom commonly encountered. An example of such a system might be a hinged raft where the platform is free to move in the traditional 6 degrees of freedom and able to bend in the middle. Another example use of &#39;additional modes&#39; would allow the modelling of a continuous system with flexible elements such as a floating rubber tube. This section contains a short guide to generating coefficients for modelling additional modes in NEMOH. Note that the terms additional mode and generalised modes are used interchangeably.

The general procedure for generating hydrodynamic coefficients for additional modes in NEMOH is shown in Figure 6. It is assumed that the user is capable of:

- generating the standard NEMOH input files (&#39;_ID.dat&#39;_, &#39;_input.txt&#39;_, &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;_ etc.)
- running the NEMOH &#39;_preProcessor&#39;_, &#39;_solver&#39;_ and &#39;_postProcessor&#39;_
- reading the standard NEMOH output files

Thus, this short guide will focus on how to modify the files generated by the NEMOH &#39;_preProcessor_&#39; in order to define the additional modes. The only requirement is that the &#39;_Nemoh.cal_&#39;file defines a sufficient number of modes that are required in the hydrodynamic coefficients (the sum of the standard (traditional) and additional modes).

Figure 6: Procedure for generating hydrodynamic coefficients for additional modes in NEMOH

Essentially to generate the additional modes three files need to be modified:

1. &#39;_Integration.dat&#39;_
2. _&#39;Normalvelocities.dat_&#39;
3. &#39;_FKforce.tec&#39;_

1.
  1. 1.23Modification of the &#39;_Integration.dat_&#39; file

The &#39;_Integration.dat_&#39; file contains an array of integration factors for each panel on the body surface and for each hydrodynamic mode. The value of this integration factor is set to be the product of the panel area and the orthogonal amplitude of motion of the panel centre in the direction of the degree of freedom. However, the panel area does not appear to be directly available in NEMOH and so it is necessary to modify the integration factor from the nominal hydrodynamic mode, taking into account the change in orientation of the nominal mode to the new additional mode. Details of the format of the file are available in &#39;_Section_ _5.1.2 __Integration.dat__&#39;_. A Matlab routine for reading the file is provided in Appendix A  although this has worked, care should be taken since this has not been extensively tested.

1.
  1. 1.24Modification of the &#39;_Normalvelocities.dat&#39;_ file

The &#39;_Normalvelocities.dat&#39;_ file contains an array of normal velocities for each panel on the body surface and for each hydrodynamic mode. The values in this array need to be modified in the additional modes so that they equal the normal velocities for the additional modes. Details of the format of the &#39;_Normalvelocities.dat&#39;_ file are available in &#39;_Section_ _5.1.1__Normalvelocities.dat_&#39;. A Matlab routine for reading the file is provided in Appendix A  although this has worked, care should be taken since this has not been extensively tested.

1.
  1. 1.25Modification of the &#39;_FKforce.tec_&#39; file

The &#39;_FKforce.tec&#39;_file contains the calculation of the Froude-Krylov force for each of the hydrodynamic modes. This needs to be re-calculated so that it is correct for the additional modes. The Froude-Krylov force can typically simply be re-calculated using the integral of the incident wave pressure and the integration factor for each hydrodynamic mode. Note, currently the &#39;_FKforce.tec&#39;_file is used by NEMOH to calculate the Froude-Krylov force, not the &#39;_FKforce.dat&#39;_, which would be expected. In the future this may change and so care needs to be taken with any upgrades of the NEMOH software. A Matlab routine for reading the file is provided in Appendix A  although this has worked, care should be taken since this has not been extensively tested.

1.
  1. 1.26Example

To illustrate the generation of coefficients for additional modes consider the case of a vertical flap where it is required to define an additional mode where the flap deformation displacement is proportional to the square of the distance from the flap axis. To define an additional mode this deformation must be related to a particular displacement; for simplicity the deformation is defined as the amplitude of motion at the top of the flap1.

Assuming that the flap is vertical and the deformation is orthogonal to the flap then the most convenient nominal mode, which must be defined in the &#39;_Nemoh.cal&#39;_file is surge. Using surge as the nominal mode, which is overwritten by the additional mode, then the integration factors on the front and back faces of the flap can simply be defined by

I=I0(dD)2

where I is the integration factor for the new mode, I0 is the integration factor for the surge mode, D is the distance from the axis to the top of the flap and d is the vertical distance of the centre of the panel to the axis2. To achieve this it is necessary to identify which panels are on the front and back of the flap; in this case this is relatively easy because all other panels will have an integration factor of zero (assuming that the flap is a simple box shape) and so it does not matter if they are multiplied by a new factor since they will still equal zero.

The normal velocities can also be relatively easily calculated and are zero for all except the front and back faces, where the normal velocity Vn is given by

Vn=(dD)2

Finally the Froude-Krylov force requires calculation of the incident wave pressure at each panel, which is given by

p=gcoshk(z+h)coshkheik(xcos+ysin)

where  is the water density, g is the gravitational acceleration, k is the wave number, h is the water depth,  is the angle of wave incidence, x,y,z is the coordinates of the centre of the panel.

To calculate the total Froude-Krylov force this pressure needs to be multiplied by the integration factors previously calculated and then summed for all the panels on the body. It is important to remember that the values are complex and the result will also be a complex number.

Another example would be to calculate the hydrodynamic coefficients for an additional mode, where the additional mode is rigid pitching of the flap. This may be slightly more complex to calculate the new integration factors since the bottom of the flap will also make a contribution and the normal velocity will also need a slightly different definition due to the finite width of the flap. However, the significantly advantage of this as a test example is that the hydrodynamic coefficients could be compared to the coefficients calculated by NEMOH using the standard pitching mode.
